In the field of machine learning, transformer architectures have  revolutionized the way models process and learn from data, especially in natural language processing (NLP).  These models rely on mechanisms that enable them to pay attention to relevant parts of the input data, allowing for more efficient and context-aware processing.  This self-attention mechanism is a crucial component of the transformer's success. However, the traditional self-attention mechanism has limitations in terms of computational efficiency, especially when dealing with long sequences of data.  This project proposes an exploration of the Global Nearest Neighbor Attention (GNN-Attention) mechanism as an efficient alternative to the traditional self-attention.  The primary objective is to compare the performance and efficiency of GNN-Attention with standard self-attention in transformer models.
\subsection{Motivation}
The motivation for this project stems from the growing need for more efficient and scalable transformer models, particularly in applications where processing long sequences is essential.  As the demand for handling larger data volumes increases, the computational costs associated with the self-attention mechanism, which are quadratic in the sequence length, become a_xlabeling issue.  The GNN-Attention mechanism, by contrast, offers a potential reduction in computational complexity by focusing on the most relevant tokens  in the sequence, thus enabling the model to maintain high performance while reducing the resources
